  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Surgical day unit&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;I have been on this unit twice now and in 2 years nothing has improved. When I booked in the corridor was full of patients and relatives with inadequate seating and it only opened on the dot of 07.00. Why ask people to come in for 07.00 and if they arrive early they have to wait. can staff on the unit not cope with booking in a patient or why not have a booking in machine in the waiting area. The letter doesn't even say where to go to be booked in. Got into the waiting room and was the only person to wash my hands despite notices. No-one should be allowed on the unit without washing their hands. A note on the door says no relatives on the ward and then guess what? Patients are called and the relatives pile in with them but aren't stopped. The nurses don't seem to appreciate that patients have needs and they can be found in a huddle at the desk rather than checking to see if patients are ok once the patients have been settled on the unit. You cannot call them as there are no buzzers so you just sit there waiting. If you do get the chance to see someone and ask it is always I'll come back. Right this side of Christmas or what? The door into the waiting area should be an automatic door to help people who might have disabilities. If money can be found to  re-brand A&amp;amp;amp;E at such cost then this door can be changed. My bag wasn't labelled before I went to theatre and the nurse weren't bothered to find out the correct information. So I arrive on a unit with my bag missing which then had to be tracked down. That is sloppy nursing. This unit needs a good shake up because to find the same things 2 years apart isn't good. The door into the theatre area blocks the corridor to the toilets and at some point a  patient will be send flying if coming out of the toilet and that big door opens. That is dangerous and when it is open you have to squeeze past through a narrow gap which isn't safe. You then get asked similar questions to those in pre-op so what is the point of pre-op? This unit isn't giving Salford a good name.&lt;/CommentText&gt;
